              <h2>
                <strong>Learn</strong><span class="tags"> in <a href="/technology">Technology</a>, <a href="/transportation">Transportation</a> and <a href="/cities">Cities</a></span></h2>
              <time datetime="2010-11-19T19:00:00Z" pubdate="pubdate">November 19, 2010</time>
            </div>
            <h1>Would an Hourglass Traffic Light Work Better?</h1>
            <div class="body"><p>	<img alt="" id="asset_262166" src="http://pre.cloudfront.goodinc.com/posts/full_129019433319.jpg" /><br />	Mark Frauenfelder <a href="http://www.boingboing.net/2010/11/19/hourglass-traffic-li.html">found</a> this <a href="http://www.yankodesign.com/2010/11/18/sands-of-traffic-times/">interesting new traffic light design</a> by Thanva Tivawong. LED lights trickle down like sand in a virtual hourglass, letting you know when the light will change. I actually find this to be pretty confusing the more I look at it&mdash;a simple numerical countdown or a design like <a href="http://www.good.is/post/Is-This-a-Better-Traffic-Light-Hard-to-Say">Damjan Stankovic&#39;s</a> might be clearer&mdash;but Tivawong&#39;s proposal does make you think about the opportunities for improving traffic lights.</p></div>
            <div class="drawer">
              <div class="actions"></div>
              <div class="voters"></div>
            </div></article>
